THE recent appearance of the “ Public School Latin Primer‚’' and the publication of “ White’s J unior Scholar's Latin-English Dictionary '’ in the earlier part of the year, have induced the Editor to bring into harmony with their principles certain of his Elementary Classical Works, viz.: his editions of Bradley‘s Eutropius and Phaedrus, together with that of Valpy’s Latin Delectus. In these so much has been dqne, and so completely have their respec- tive N otes and Vocabularies been altered, in order to meet the existing state of scholarship, that they may fairly be regarded as new works, rather than as new editions.

Observations upon certain passages, and the ex- planation of points of a purely grammatical nature, have been alone retained in the Notes, remarks upon construction being worded in accordance with the terminology of the “ Public School Latin Primer '' and accompanied with references to the rules of its Syntax.
